{{Short description|Vice President of the Maldives from 2012 to 2013}} {{Use British English|date=November 2023}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2023}} {{Infobox officeholder | name = Mohamed Waheed Deen | native_name = އައް ނަބީލް މުޙައްމަދު ވަހީދުއްދީން | native_name_lang = dv | image = | caption = | office = [[Vice President of the Maldives]] | president = [[Mohammed Waheed Hassan]] | term_start = 25 April 2012 | term_end = 10 November 2013 | predecessor = Mohammed Waheed Hassan | successor = [[Mohamed Jameel Ahmed]] | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | party = | otherparty = | spouse = | children = | alma_mater = }}
'''Al Amir Mohammed Waheed Deen''' ({{lang-dv|އައް ނަބީލް މުޙައްމަދު ވަހީދުއްދީން}}) is a Maldivian politician who served [[vice president of the Maldives]] from 25 April 2012 to 10 November 2013. He was appointed to the position by President [[Mohamed Waheed Hassan]] on 15 February 2012, following the disputed resignation of the previous president, [[Mohamed Nasheed]].<ref name=minivan>{{cite web |author=JJ Robinson and Hawwa Lubna |url=http://minivannews.com/politics/waheed-deen-nominated-as-vice-president-32174 |title=Waheed Deen nominated as Vice President |publisher=Minivan News |date=15 February 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109105516/http://minivannews.com/politics/waheed-deen-nominated-as-vice-president-32174 |archivedate=9 November 2013 }}</ref> He is also the Chairman of Bandos Maldives.<ref name=minivan/>
Deen is the son of Prince Abdullah Imaaduddeen and Koli Dhon Didi. He is also a member of the Maldivian Royal Family as his grandfather was Sultan [[Muhammad Imaaduddeen IV]].<ref>Haveeru News on 15th February 2012 , Maldives Royal Family Website </ref> He previously served as Minister of Atolls Development and Minister of Youth and Sports until August 2008 under [[Maumoon Abdul Gayoom]].<ref name=minivan/><ref>{{cite web|author=Shantanu Guha Ray |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/maldives-india-ties-mohamed-waheed-mohammed-nasheed/1/188636.html |title=Maldives President Mohamed Waheed seeks predecessor Mohammed Nasheed's involvement to solve political crisis |publisher=India Today |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2013}}</ref> He resigned from the Vice President’s post hours before the end of the presidential term, and after the country’s last ditch attempt to elect a new president before the constitutional deadline of November 11 failed after the Supreme Court suspended the runoff which was slated for 10 November. Neither the Vice President nor the Government stated the cause of the resignation. [[File:USS John C. Stennis operations 130327-N-TC437-199.jpg|thumb|Sideboys welcoming Deen]]
